Most African countries are bearing the brunt of the US-China trade war, as well as a slump in commodity prices which is greatly affecting exporters, therefore leading to a potential sluggish pace in growth rate.
   
This is according to the latest report from ICAEW – the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales – Economic Update: Africa Q3 2019.
  
The report provides gross domestic product (GDP) growth forecasts for various regions including East Africa, which is set to grow by 6.3 per cent, West and Central Africa at 3.4 per cent, Franc Zone at 4.7 per cent, and Southern Africa at 1.3 per cent.  To enable commenting and other interactive features, please switch to the more advanced .